1. JSON-LD 1.1: syntax and data model (technical facts)
- JSON-LD documents are JSON objects containing optional @context and one or more node objects. A term mapping in @context maps a short term to an IRI, or to an IRI plus coercion rules ("@id", "@type").
- Keywords: @context, @id, @type, @value, @language, @list, @set, @graph, @reverse, @included, @vocab, @base, @container, @index.
- Forms: Expanded form (fully-qualified IRIs, explicit object structures), Compacted form (short terms via context), Flattened form (all nodes at top level), Framed form (tree-shaped output per frame).
- Data model rules: values are objects with either @id or @value; lists are explicit with @list; blank nodes are represented by generated identifiers when mapping to RDF; node identifiers and IRIs resolved relative to base IRI or vocabulary mapping per context.
- Relationship to RDF: JSON-LD defines deterministic algorithms to serialize to and from RDF (toRDF/fromRDF), and normalization/canonicalization (URDNA2015) using N-Quads as the canonical serialization for datasets.

2. JSON-LD processing algorithms (implementation-level steps)
- Context processing: create-term-definition constructs a mapping from term -> {iri, typeMapping, container, language, index, reverse, protected} per context entries; supports remote contexts via document loader.
- Expansion algorithm: recursively expand compacted terms to full IRIs, convert values to object form, apply @type/@id coercions, handle @language and typed values, generate node map for flattening.
- Compaction algorithm: using an inverse context, choose shortest term or compact IRI by comparing term selection rules and container expectations; compaction can be lossy if contexts do not preserve structural distinctions.
- Flattening: generate a node map keyed by identifier and merge graph-level nodes; used to produce a uniform set of nodes for framing and canonicalization.
- RDF serialization/deserialization: Object-to-RDF rules: value objects map to triples with rdf:rest/rdf:first for lists, typed literals use datatypes, @id become subject/object IRIs, blank nodes use generated labels; Data-round-tripping defined by specific conversion algorithms in the spec.
- Canonicalization: URDNA2015 algorithm produces deterministic N-Quads ordering for datasets to enable hashing/signing.

3. JSON-LD API and options (spec-level contract)
- JsonLdProcessor interface (API names and core semantics): expand(input, options) => expanded document; compact(input, context, options) => compacted document; flatten(input, context?, options?) => flattened document; frame(input, frame, options) => framed document; toRDF(input, options) => RDF dataset (format option controls serialization such as application/n-quads); fromRDF(dataset, options) => JSON-LD document; canonize(input, options) => canonical N-Quads string; registerRDFParser(contentType, parserFn) and registerRDFParser async/sync variants.
- JsonLdOptions (common fields): base (IRI), documentLoader (url -> {contextUrl, document, documentUrl}), processingMode (e.g., 'json-ld-1.1'), expandContext, compactArrays, safe (boolean triggers errors on lossy operations), algorithm (for canonize e.g., 'URDNA2015'), format (output MIME for toRDF), skipExpansion (internal/test use).
- Document loader contract: given URL and options, must return an object with keys {contextUrl|null, document, documentUrl} where document is the retrieved JSON-LD or related document; loaders may implement caching, preloaded contexts and custom headers.
- Safe mode: when options.safe true, processors detect transformations that would drop information and fail rather than silently drop it (useful for canonicalization and signatures).

4. RDF 1.1 data model (implementer-level definitions)
- Triple = subject predicate object where subject is an IRI or blank node, predicate is an IRI, object is an IRI, literal, or blank node.
- IRI resolution: IRIs in JSON-LD or RDF are resolved relative to base IRI rules (RFC3987 semantics) except vocabulary-relative terms in JSON-LD contexts which use the vocabulary mapping.
- Literals: typed literals include a datatype IRI; language-tagged strings use rdf:langString implicitly with language tag stored separately; literals only appear in object position.
- Blank nodes: internal identifiers with no global IRI; many libraries prefix or remap labels to prevent collisions when merging datasets.
- Datasets: named graphs supported; canonical serialization for datasets is N-Quads; common conversions between JSON-LD node maps and RDF datasets are specified by the JSON-LD algorithms.

5. OWL 2 (implementation-relevant rules and profiles)
- OWL 2 ontologies can be represented as RDF graphs using the OWL 2 Mapping to RDF Graphs. All OWL 2 constructs have corresponding RDF triple encodings per the Mapping document.
- Semantics: Direct Semantics maps OWL structures to SROIQ description logic models (used by DL reasoners); RDF-Based Semantics directly assigns meaning to RDF graphs (used for OWL Full style reasoning). A correspondence theorem exists linking Direct and RDF-Based Semantics for OWL 2 DL ontologies.
- Profiles and intended effects: OWL 2 EL (polynomial-time reasoning for very large ontologies); OWL 2 QL (conjunctive query answering via SQL rewrites); OWL 2 RL (rule-based reasoning over triples, suitable for triple store execution). Choose profile per performance/expressivity needs.
- Key OWL constructs of implementation interest: keys, property chains, qualified cardinality restrictions, asymmetric/reflexive/disjoint properties, annotation properties; these map to RDF triples and require special handling in rule engines and DL reasoners.
- Conformance: RDF/XML exchange syntax is mandatory for full conformance; however Turtle, Manchester, OWL/XML are commonly supported by tools. Test suites exist in the OWL 2 conformance documents.

6. Libraries and SDKs (concrete API signatures and behavior)
6.1 jsonld.js (digitalbazaar/jsonld.js)
- Core async API functions and typical signatures:
  jsonld.compact(input, context, options?) -> Promise<object>
  jsonld.expand(input, options?) -> Promise<array|object> (expanded arrays)
  jsonld.flatten(input, contextOrOptions?, options?) -> Promise<object>
  jsonld.frame(input, frame, options?) -> Promise<object>
  jsonld.toRDF(input, options?) -> Promise<string|Dataset> where options.format controls output (default application/n-quads)
  jsonld.fromRDF(dataset, options?) -> Promise<object>
  jsonld.canonize(input, options?) -> Promise<string> using algorithm option (e.g., URDNA2015)
  jsonld.registerRDFParser(contentType, parserFn) -> void
  jsonld.documentLoader = customLoaderFn (url, options) -> {contextUrl, document, documentUrl}
- Implementation notes from library: built-in document loaders for Node and XHR; recommended to set Node document loader default user-agent to 'jsonld.js' for HTTP fetches; safe option to detect lossy behavior; custom RDF parsers can be registered; canonize supports URDNA2015 and output formatting.

6.2 N3.js (rdfjs/N3.js)
- Data factory helpers and signatures:
  const { DataFactory } = N3; const { namedNode, literal, defaultGraph, quad } = DataFactory;
  quad(subject: Term, predicate: Term, object: Term, graph?: Term) -> Quad
- Parser / stream interfaces:
  const parser = new N3.Parser(options?); parser.parse(input, callback(error, quad, prefixes)) parses synchronously or accepts a stream; options: { format, baseIRI, blankNodePrefix, isImpliedBy }
  const streamParser = new N3.StreamParser(); streamParser is a Node.js stream and RDFJS Sink.
- Writer interfaces:
  const writer = new N3.Writer({ prefixes, format? }); writer.addQuad(quad); writer.end(callback(error, resultString)) serializes as Turtle/TriG/N-Triples/N-Quads per format.
- Store API and dataset semantics:
  const store = new N3.Store(); store.add(quad) store.match(subject?, predicate?, object?, graph?) -> iterator/array; store.getQuads(...) returns array; store.size property; Dataset interface mapping per RDFJS dataset spec.
- Options that affect behavior: parser blankNodePrefix to avoid label collisions; parser baseIRI for relative IRI resolution; writer flags to control abbreviation and JSON-LD conversion flags (e.g., 'dr', 'o').

6.3 rdflib.js (linkeddata/rdflib.js)
- Key API signatures and behavior:
  graph() -> Store (kb)
  sym(iri: string) -> NamedNode
  serialize(doc, kb, baseIRI, mimeType, callbackOrUndefined, options?) -> string (serialized RDF in mimeType)
  serialize accepts options.flags string which alters abbreviation/formatting behavior; flags include 'dr', 'o', 'p', and combined flags like 'o k'.
- Features: read/write RDF/XML, Turtle and N3; reads RDFa and JSON-LD; built-in Linked Data client (Fetcher) and Update Manager for SPARQL/Update; smushing rules for owl:sameAs; serializer flags to tune output abbreviation and JSON-LD conversion.
- Important options: serializer flags 'dr' (JSON-LD conversion), 'o' (do not abbreviate dotted local parts), 'p' disables prefix abbreviations entirely.

7. Implementation patterns and pipelines (concrete steps)
- Common pipeline for consuming JSON-LD in application and reasoning over OWL:
  1) Load JSON-LD via jsonld.js with a custom documentLoader that caches contexts and enforces HTTPS and user-agent headers.
  2) Call jsonld.toRDF(doc, {format: 'application/n-quads'}) to obtain N-Quads canonicalizable by URDNA2015.
  3) Optionally canonize using jsonld.canonize(doc, {algorithm: 'URDNA2015', format: 'application/n-quads'}) for signing or diffs.
  4) Parse N-Quads with N3.Parser or import into an RDF triple store (N3.Store or rdflib.js graph) for storage and SPARQL queries.
  5) If OWL reasoning required, ensure RDF graph conforms to OWL profile constraints or feed to an OWL DL reasoner after mapping via OWL 2 RDF mappings. For large-scale rule-based reasoning prefer OWL 2 RL and rule engines operating directly on triple stores.
- Streaming and memory handling: use N3.StreamParser and N3.StreamWriter for files larger than memory; use N3.Store or persistent triple store for datasets > memory.

8. Configuration options and effects (concrete values)
- jsonld.js options:
  documentLoader: function(url, options) -> {contextUrl, document, documentUrl} ; effect: overrides remote fetching and enables caching or preloaded contexts.
  safe: boolean ; true => throw on lossy compaction/operations used for canonicalization.
  algorithm: 'URDNA2015' ; canonicalization algorithm for canonize. format: 'application/n-quads' recommended for canonical N-Quads.
  processingMode: 'json-ld-1.1' ; ensures spec rules for 1.1 processing.
- N3.js options:
  N3.Parser({ format: 'N-Triples'|'N3'|'Turtle'|'TriG', baseIRI: string, blankNodePrefix: string, isImpliedBy: boolean }) ; effect: controls parsing mode, blank node label prefixing, and notation support.
  N3.Writer({ prefixes: {p:iri}, format: 'text/turtle'|'application/trig'|'N-Triples' }) ; effect: controls output serialization.
- rdflib.js options:
  serialize flags string (e.g., 'o', 'dr', 'p') ; effect: abbreviation and JSON-LD conversion behavior.

9. Best practices and troubleshooting recipes
- Context caching: implement a document loader cache keyed by resolved context URL and documentUrl; return the cached document object with contextUrl null when preloaded.
- Avoiding blank node collisions: when merging graphs from multiple sources, set N3.Parser({ blankNodePrefix: 'siteA_' }) to namespace local blank nodes, or use unique baseIRI per source before generating blank node labels.
- Detecting lossy compaction: use jsonld.expand then jsonld.compact with safe: true to ensure compaction does not lose typed/value distinctions; for signing use canonize with safe mode.
- RDF round trips: to verify JSON-LD <-> RDF round trip, use jsonld.toRDF and jsonld.fromRDF and compare canonicalized N-Quads; differences indicate context or coercion mismatches.
- Canonicalization failures: URDNA2015 requires consistent blank node labels derived from graph structure; if canonicalization yields differing outputs across implementations, ensure same RDF dataset serialization and same algorithm parameters.
- Performance: prefer JSON-LD expansion and toRDF for normalization then streaming parse with N3 for ingestion into stores; for very large datasets, avoid in-memory node maps and use streaming transforms.

10. Supplementary details (spec excerpts and exact behavior)
- Document loader return object format: { contextUrl: null | string, document: any, documentUrl: string }
- jsonld.registerRDFParser(contentType, parserFn) signature: parserFn(input) -> Dataset or Promise<Dataset>, where Dataset follows jsonld.js internal dataset shape or an RDFJS Dataset depending on options. Registering allows custom MIME handling.
- jsonld.canonize(input, { algorithm: 'URDNA2015', format: 'application/n-quads' }) returns a Promise resolving to a canonical N-Quads string. Use this string for deterministic hashing and signature generation.
- N3.Writer end(callback) yields serialized string; provide prefixes to writer to shorten output; flags influence abbreviation behavior for Turtle and JSON-LD conversion.

TROUBLESHOOTING CHECKLIST
- If contexts fail to load: verify documentLoader, network, and Content-Type headers; return object must include documentUrl matching final redirect.
- If blank nodes collide: set distinct blankNodePrefix per source or merge via canonicalization which reassigns deterministic blank node identifiers.
- If compaction loses information: run in safe mode or perform expand -> toRDF -> canonize and compare canonical forms.
- If RDF round-trip differs: compare canonical N-Quads produced by toRDF+canonize for both source and round-tripped document.

